0 Census and Related Issues" to Cathy Irwin and Sean Metzger's "Keeping Up Appearances: Ethnic Alien-Nation in Female Solo Performance," this diverse collection spans the realities of multiculturalism in compelling new analysis. Arguing that society's discomfort with multiracialism has been institutionalized throughout history, whether through the "one drop" rule or media depictions, SanSan Kwan and Kenneth Speirs reflect on the means by which the monoracial lens is slowly being replaced. Itself a hybrid of memoir, history, and sociological theory, Mixing It Up makes it clear why the identity politics of previous decades have little relevance to the fluid new face of contemporary humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCultural pluralismzUnited States. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aPerforming artsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aRacially mixed people in literature. 0aRacially mixed peoplexRace identityzUnited States. 0aRacially mixed peoplezUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRacially mixed peoplezUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Biracial & Multiracial Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlsultany, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarton, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeSouza, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunning, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwan, SanSan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwan, SanSan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNorthern, Orathai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalgado, Raquel S